<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="collection and habitat data">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Collection and habitat data.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bembidion rufotinctum" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufotinctum">Bembidion rufotinctum</taxonomicName>
lives in cracks of emergent bedrock in river channels (
<bibRefCitation author="Cooper, KW" journalOrPublisher="Entomological News" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="159 - 166" title="Rediscovery of Bembidion rufotinctum Chaudoir, with extreme range and distributional records of Bembidion and the other Carabidae (Coleoptera)." volume="87" year="1976">Cooper 1976</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Davidson, R" journalOrPublisher="The Coleopterists Bulletin" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="127 - 128" title="Note on the distribution and habitat of Bembidion (Pseudoperyphus) rufotinctum Chaudoir (Coleoptera: Carabidae) in Vermont, New Hampshire, and Virginia." volume="35" year="1981">Davidson 1981</bibRefCitation>
). A typical habitat for this species is illustrated by Maddison (2008; Fig. 1 D, p. 148). In New Brunswick, adults were collected during May and September by splashing exposed bed rock adjacent to fast-flowing water above a waterfall. It took 5-10 min. before the adults appeared on the exposed rock surfaces. The exposed bedrock at this site was similar to that illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Maddison, DR" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Carnegie Museum" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="147 - 193" title="Systematics of the North American beetle subgenus Pseudoperyphus (Coleoptera: Carabidae: Bembidion) based on morphological, chromosomal, and molecular data." url="10.2992/0097-4463-77.1.147" volume="77" year="2008">Maddison (2008)</bibRefCitation>
, although less extensive.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Distribution in Canada and Alaska.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
QC, NB (
<bibRefCitation pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Bousquet 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Maddison, DR" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Carnegie Museum" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="147 - 193" title="Systematics of the North American beetle subgenus Pseudoperyphus (Coleoptera: Carabidae: Bembidion) based on morphological, chromosomal, and molecular data." url="10.2992/0097-4463-77.1.147" volume="77" year="2008">Maddison 2008</bibRefCitation>
). The closest localities of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bembidion rufotinctum" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufotinctum">Bembidion rufotinctum</taxonomicName>
to New Brunswick are in Quebec, Ste.-
<normalizedToken originalValue="Raphaël">Raphael</normalizedToken>
, Bellechasse Co., on exposed bedrock near waterfalls along the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Rivière">Riviere</normalizedToken>
du Sud (Webster, unpublished), and in New Hampshire (
<bibRefCitation author="Maddison, DR" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Carnegie Museum" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="147 - 193" title="Systematics of the North American beetle subgenus Pseudoperyphus (Coleoptera: Carabidae: Bembidion) based on morphological, chromosomal, and molecular data." url="10.2992/0097-4463-77.1.147" volume="77" year="2008">Maddison 2008</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bembidion rufotinctum" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufotinctum">Bembidion rufotinctum</taxonomicName>
has not yet been reported from Maine (
<bibRefCitation author="Majka, CG" journalOrPublisher="Empty Mirrors Press, Halifax, Nova Scotia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" title="Checklist of the beetles of Maine, USA." year="2011">Majka et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
) but will undoubtedly be found in the state once appropriate habitats are sampled.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
